snippet.textDisplay: That watch is worn. The reference sticker is worn out. That looks like at least 12 months of use. If it was unworn it would be green. The bracelet clasp has corrosion on it by its hinges. The Rolex crown on the clasp looks like it was polished and doesn’t look sharp. Some “experts” will question the blank papers. In this case it’s ok because he bought this on a military base canteen (ordered it). Still anyone can buy these. But.... where’s the serial number printed (hole punched) on the warranty. I have to question that. The bezel looks like it has some wear. The price seems about correct for 1975. The fact that it’s a 1971 watch bought in 75 seems about right. Rolex couldn’t really sell Daytona’s because they were considered the dogs of Rolex. Nobody wanted them. Rolex at one point was going to discontinue the Daytona line. Another thing this man does not look like he is old enough to have been in his early 20’s in 1971. The hair looks like a wig, and this guy sounds like he speaks with a Canadian accent. I will say this watch is NOT worth $700k. It is worth $100k - $200k for sure but not $700k. Great story for tv

snippet.textDisplay: It is a great story and my hat is off to our veteran friend. On the watch, it is a highly collectible and sought after watch. That said, I disagree with the appraiser’s call that it’s in NOS condition. This watch has clearly been worn and used quite a bit. There is patina on the dial and Lume. The sub dials are faded... the watch has clearly been in the sunlight. The Rolex stamped logos on the clasp blades are worn down and almost unrecognizable. Also there is grime on the blades and around the crown and pushers. This watch may have been stored for decades but not before considerable wear.  Given all that, the watch is still highly collectible.

snippet.textDisplay: Nice entertainment folks but let’s get real.  This is not a new old stock watch.  The watch definitely has signs of significant wear.  Scratches on the Bezel and bracelet,  trapped grime in the links.  The Rolex logo on the bracelet alone has been worn down from many years of use.  This watch has definitely been worn more than the few times mentioned in the Video.  The condition of sticker on the back is clear evidence of what I would say is a few  years of wearing on the wrist.  Significant wear, grime and sweat on the wrist will do exactly what you see on the sticker.  $700k not worth it.  The watch in my opinion can easily fetch a fair market price of $200k but I am sure there is someone out there that would definitely pay more.  I hope this military man can get $700k or more if he wishes to sell it.  He deserves millions for his service.  A real hero!
